Equities in South Africa Rally for 6th Day; Massmart, Mondi, Pan African

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-05-31T16:10:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/equities-in-south-africa-rise-for-6th-day-mondi-pan-african-sasol-move.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
gained for a sixth day, adding 175.82, or 0.5 percent, to
32,565.73 at the 5 p.m. close of trade in Johannesburg, paring
its loss this month to 0.8 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  ,  South Africa ’s biggest
food and general goods wholesaler, rose 2.46 rand, or 1.8
percent, to 142.56 rand, the highest close since May 3. The
country’s anti-trust authorities approved Wal-Mart Stores Inc.’s
purchase of a controlling stake in the South African company.
 Pick n Pay Stores Ltd. (PIK)  , the country’s second-largest
grocer, added 59 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 43.40 rand, the
highest closing level since April 15.  Shoprite Holdings Ltd. (SHP)  , South Africa’s largest
retailer by market value, increased for a third day, rallying
1.03 rand, or 1 percent, to 99.60 rand.  Mondi Ltd. (MND)  ,  Europe ’s largest maker of office
paper, jumped 1.64 rand, or 2.5 percent, to 66.69 rand, the
highest close since April 2008. The company said it will spin
off and list Mondi Packaging South Africa Ltd. on July 11.  Pan African Resources Plc (PAF)  , a gold exploration
company, headed for the strongest close since April 11, rising 3
cents, or 2.6 percent, 1.18 rand. Its total  mineral resources 
increased by 7 percent to 2.55 million ounces of gold at its
Barberton Mines unit.  SacOil Holding Ltd. (SCL)  , an oil and natural gas
explorer, rose for a third day, adding 6 cents, or 5.7 percent,
to 1.12 rand. Oil rose as much as 2.8 percent to $103.39 a
barrel.  Sentula Mining Ltd. (SNU)  , a coal miner, advanced for a
sixth day, rallying 15 cents, or 5.5 percent, 2.87 rand. The
mining company said it expects per share earnings after one-time
items to be at least 16 cents in the year through March,
according to a trading update published today. Sentula also
suspended operations at its Nkomati anthracite mine, pending
resolution of a regulatory matter.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-
line operator, increased the most since May 24, rising 17 cents,
or 0.5 percent, to 36.40 rand. The company said it will report a
loss in the year ended March, compared with a restated profit of
8 billion rand ($12 million) a year earlier, according to a
regulatory statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
